{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"84de4ea0-f64f-4f6f-b0c3-89f68086780d","content":"A **NullReferenceException** is an application-level bug — it means your code is dereferencing a `null` object at runtime. **CLR activation logs** won't help here; those logs diagnose which .NET runtime version gets loaded (e.g., wrong runtime selected, runtime not found, v2/v4 conflicts).\n\n**To diagnose your NullReferenceException, you need:**\n\n1. **The stack trace** from the exception — it tells you exactly which line has the null dereference.\n2. **Application logs** or a **crash dump** — not CLR activation logs.\n\n**Quick fixes to try:**\n- Run your app with a debugger attached and break on the exception.\n- Check the exception's `StackTrace` property for the faulting method and line number.\n- Look for uninitialized fields, missing DI registrations, or race conditions during startup.\n\nWould you like help with any of these instead? If you do have CLR activation logs and suspect a runtime-loading issue (e.g., wrong .NET version being picked up), I can help with that too.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e1e6331d-705d-4658-ac75-abe621a39669","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, a NullReferenceException after startup is not really a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs deal with which runtime version gets loaded, not application-level exceptions like NullReferenceException. Let me think about whether the skill is appropriate here.\n\n\nThe skill is specifically for CLR activation problems—things like the shim loading the wrong runtime, FOD dialogs, or multiple runtimes in the same process. A NullReferenceException is an application-level bug that happens after the runtime is already running, so CLR activation logs won't help diagnose it. I should explain this distinction to the user rather than use the skill.","outputTokens":636,"requestId":"AC03:EB431:160A10F:18C2AFC:6A067AF5"},"id":"d5f52743-3df0-4ff1-a76e-3194d619d9a8","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:46:45.703Z","parentId":"8036ec91-f56e-45ab-a691-5d8a42ee1748"}
